custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Copy: On December 6, 1888, after traveling nearly 6,000 miles in a Dutch immigrate ship, a 21-year-old printer’s apprentice by the name of Harry Koch finally stepped foot in the land of opportunity.

America was brimming with promise and Harry wasted no time after arriving in New York City in search for making his aspirations a reality. In just three years, Harry found himself working at Dutch newspapers in Michigan and Chicago, traveling down the Mississippi to Louisiana and working his way west to three towns in Texas before putting down roots in Quanah, Texas.

custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Highlight: Fred takes a much different route
custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Copy: It was there Harry bought and helped turn around a print shop and struggling weekly newspaper called the Quanah Chief. He and his wife had two sons, Anton and Fred. While Anton went to work for his father as an advertising manager for the newspaper, Fred decided to take a much different route.

While his dad had a strong grasp on the written word, Fred Koch’s gift revolved around math and science. After receiving exemplary marks in high school, Fred chose to attend the Rice Institute in Houston, Texas, five years after its inception.

After his sophomore year, Fred decided to transfer to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to be a part of their inaugural chemical engineering program class. The tuition was a whopping $300 a year and it was worth every penny. His senior thesis was the first public look at Fred’s ingenuity and resourcefulness. In it, he laid out his environmental idea to take a waste product from a pulp mill and reuse it as fuel. This idea was the culmination of an impressive collegiate resume and helped land Fred a job at the Texas Company (now know as Texaco) as a research chemist before graduation. But it wasn’t long before Fred wanted more.
custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Subtitle: Fred joins the inaugural chemical engineering program at MIT

custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Copy: “The Utilization of Spent Black Ash from the Soda Recovery System of the Penobscot Chemical Fibre Company” in the caption.
In 1924, Fred Koch was hired to design and construct a refinery in England after being recommended by a former MIT classmate. There he met Charles de Ganahl, an entrepreneur and the man in charge.
custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Subtitle: In England Fred meets Charles de Ganahl
The life of Charles de Ganahl

custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Copy: It wasn’t long before the respect and appreciation was mutual. By the time the refinery was up and running, Charles was calling Fred “the soundest chemical engineer in the world.” The two men continued to correspond after Fred returned stateside. Later in life, Charles became involved in numerous organizations including serving on the board for the Memorial Hospital for cancer treatment in New York City.
custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Subtitle: Charles de Ganahl and Fred strike up a friendship based on respect and appreciation

custom_KochTimelineModule.Module_Copy:
On his way back from England to visit his family in Quanah, Texas, Fred Koch made a quick detour that would change the trajectory of a company and his life forever.
The fateful stop was in Wichita, Kansas, to visit Percival “Dobie” Keith, Jr., a former MIT classmate. Dobie had recently established a engineering consulting firm with Lewis Winkler. Pleasantries quickly turned to talk of business and just like that, Fred bought a one-third share in the company for $300.

The three partners worked on designing and constructing distillation columns as well as providing engineering services for independent refineries. But only 3 months after Keith, Winkler & Koch Engineering was established, Dobie left for another job in Boston.

Instead of folding, Lewis and Fred chose to remain partners. In 1926, the established the Winkler-Koch Engineering Company. Winkler was in charge of construction and installation while Fred was handled sales and process design. With a new business came new opportunities, big dreams and high hopes. But it wasn’t long before they were dragged back to reality.
